@NODE KEYS "Keys"

  Keyboard short cuts are shown next to the appropriate menu option.  Keys
shown that do not have the 'A' (Amiga) key before them are just the key press
on it's own if lower case, or left/right shift and the key if it is upper
case.


@{B}Other non documented keys@{UB}

Cursor keys:         Scrolls the track one tile in the appropriate direction.

Shifted cursor keys: Scrolls the track one full screen in the appropriate
                     direction.


@ENDNODE


@NODE INST "Installation"
@ENDNODE


@NODE REQM "System Requirements"

@{U}System Requirements@{UU}

  XTremeEd requires an AGA compatible machine running at least V3.0+ of the
operating system software.  It appears to run in a minimum of 2 megabytes of
chip memory but would work much better with extra fast memory.  A hard disk
drive is pretty essential and as such has not been designed to work from a
floppy drive.  It will NOT run AT ALL without at least a 68020 processor.

  The Editor has been developed on a 10MB Amiga 4000/030 running at 25mHZ,
using SASC V6.51 and CygnusEd V3.5 as well as some rather nifty ARexx
Scripts.

@ENDNODE


@NODE EUSE "Editor Usage Guidelines"
@{U}General Editor Usage@{UU}

  Here are some general points on using XTremeEd, these are features that are
common methods of operation for most modes of the editor.



@{U}Pulling Down the Menus@{UU}

  The right mouse button is used to pull down the menus but you may have
already noticed that the editor also uses the right mouse button.  Therefore
if you wish to access the menus make sure you move the mouse pointer up to
the top of the screen before pressing the right mouse button and they will
pull down as normal.  If the mouse pointer is further down the screen then it
will perform the appropriate editor action when it is pressed.


@{U}The Mouse Buttons@{UU}

  Generally the editor uses the left mouse button to start operation and the
right mouse button to abort them.  Sometimes the right mouse has other uses
too like selecting tiles and surfaces.  You can find out more about a
particular modes special features by reading the appropriate section of the
@{" Mode Menu " link Mode.Menu/MAIN}.


@{U}Dragging and Painting@{UU}

  Dragging is when you select something with the left mouse button like an
object and whilst keeping the button pressed, drag it to a new location
releasing the button when your finished.

  Painting is used on tiles and surfaces and is similar in operation to
dragging but rather than moving an item around, you can quickly cover large
areas of the track with your selected tile or surface by move the mouse
around with the left button depressed, this will place your item everywhere
the mouse moves.


@{U}Placing Items@{UU}

  It is common to use the left mouse button to place items at the location of
the mouse pointer.  Some operations are single placements like tiles, objects
and cameras, others like boundaries are a set of connected points set down
with multiple left mouse presses.


@{U}Aborting Operations@{UU}

  Most modes allow you to use the right mouse button to abort whatever
operation is in progress, be it an addition to the track or an edit.  If you
still have the left mouse button pressed or a rubber-banded line is active on
the display, you can press the right mouse button to cancel it.


@{U}Editing Items@{UU}

  After items have been placed they can usually be relocated by selecting
them with the left mouse button and moving them to a new location.  Releasing
the button completes the operation.


@{U}Problems with Adding New Items@{UU}

  Sometimes when you are trying to add an item to the track, you may find
that the editor keeps picking up another item close by for editing.  If you
find this is happening and you cannot add your new item, try keeping the left
or right 'Shift' key pressed whilst you start you addition and the editor
should be forced to go into add mode rather than edit the other item.

  Some options also snap points near each other, together.  Often the 'Alt' key
will avoid this happening.


@{U}Deleting Items@{UU}

  Many items can be removed/deleted by placing the mouse pointer over, or very
near to them and pressing the 'Del' key.  See @{" Deleting " link Mode.Menu/DELE} for more information on this.

@ENDNODE


@NODE OPTI "Optimisations & Other Info"

  When you are testing a bonus track, from the main menu in the game type
'IDKFA' to enable the play testing mode.  This will allow you to select bonus
tracks from single race modes as well as a few other bits.

  The editor works much better if you use one of the many mode promotion
utilities available to put the editors interlaced screen into Multiscan or
DoublePal video modes.

  DO NOT use click to front mouse utilities as these will interfere with the
way the editor performs it's display operations.

  There are a number of things which can be used to speed up track editing
and/or reduce memory usage.

  If you select the editors icon from the workbench and use the
"Icon/Information" menu (Amiga I) you will see the entry:

    DISPLAYDEPTH=4

  You can vary the value 4, between 4 and 8.  It changes the number of
colours the editor screen opens in.

    4 = 16  colours
    5 = 32  colours
    6 = 64  colours
    7 = 128 colours
    8 = 256 colours

  The higher the number of colours used, the slower the editor will update,
more memory will be needed but the it will look much nicer.

  The view menu in the editor can turn certain items on and off of the map
display, greatly improving refresh speeds.  However don't forget to turn them
back on when you wish to edit something of that type as they edit modes will
NOT function correctly if the appropriate items are not shown.


  Another thing that can speed up editing is by disabling the
"Settings/Rescale Tiles" as this can be time consuming when changing the
tracks scale, but will look much clearer is enabled.

@ENDNODE


@NODE TNAM "Track Naming Conventions"

  The game uses some rules for track names so that it can determine various
information about the track before it is loaded. These include the world
graphic to display, and what type or race it is i.e. normal, deathmatch or
a bonus track.

  The rules for naming your track are as follows:

    The track name starts with the name of the world, these names are the
  names in the worlds drawer. The world name is used to find the image
  displayed when the track is loaded. After the world name there is always
  an underscore '_' followed by either a single digit number or a 'D'.

    The number is the number of the track, this is used so that you can have
  many tracks made up from the graphics of the same world. If you place a
  'B' after the number this denotes that this track is a bonus race.

    If there is no number but a 'D' at the end then this denotes that the
  track is a death match track. The world name before it is not applicable
  in this case as a general graphic is used when loading death matches.
    Instead of the world name you can put the name of your death match track
  and use '_' for spaces & don't forget to put an underscore at the end of your
  track name before adding the 'D'.


  You can see many example of track names in the tracks drawer.

  Underscores '_' will appear as spaces in the game.

@ENDNODE


@NODE MODS "Using Your Own Music Modules in the Game"

  Modules should be standard pro-tracker format using either CIA or VBLANK
timing.  Only the first two channels are available for in-game music and the
they are best kept to between 40-60K in size though no limit other than
available chip memory is imposed on them.  It may also be possible to play 4
channel modules if the sound effects are disabled but this is untested.

  To use the module you will need to add it to the modules file located in
the "Misc" drawer where ever you have installed XTremeRacing.  The file is
called "Modules"

  All modules must be placed in the "Modules" drawer and the file name
must be less than 32 characters in length.

  The format of the modules is as follows:

    The first entry must always be:

        MODNAME       Mod.None
        MODPATTERN    0

    This is what is used if no music is selected. Your own modules (maximum
    of 16) can be added after these as follows:

        MODNAME       <your modules name>
        MODPATTERN    <last lap offset>

    "MODNAME"    is the filename of the module in the "Modules" drawer
    "MODPATTERN" is the pattern number the music should play from when
                 the last lap has started, generally this is a faster
                 more manic section of the music.

    Repeat this entry for as many modules you wish to add within the
    limitations.

@ENDNODE


